Chapter 1
Cohren
4:30 AM, Itania time. Cohren hated waking up so early. Especially because it was his responsibility to wake up all the other members of his company. Silently getting out of his bunk, he put on his combat uniform, fastened his tactical vest, and gathered the items from his locker, paying particular attention to a small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and attached his helmet to a small hook attached to his belt. The helmet was fully equipped: respirator, goggles, everything needed. After checking his ammunition pockets, he calmly left the barracks, the sound of crushed mud and ice echoing under his boots.
He took out a lighter from the pocket of his vest and a cigarette from the other. As he lit it, he took a small puff before gently opening the door. The previous week, he had had to be creative to wake up the men and women under his command. He had stopped using the preset alarm, half the time it didn't work, because everything that came out of the speakers was a faint whistling sound.
"Are you waking them up?" Cohren turned around to see Second Lieutenant Nemic approaching.
"Sure," replied Cohren.
"What are you planning to use this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and other soldiers hurried out, already dressed and equipped.
"Hello," said Craith.
"What woke you up?" asked Cohren.
"Well, first of all, we didn't want to see what you had planned to wake us up with today. Second, the first shock troops up are the first at breakfast." One of them, Ravik, replied: "And you know how bad it can be."
"You make a point, Specialist," said Cohren. He extended his hand and flipped a switch. An alarm blared inside the barracks, loud and shrill. He heard commotion inside and some activity.
"For heaven's sake, Valturi," Nemic said. "One would think they'd have learned to get up at the same time as you by now."
"Well, my training camp buddies here did it," Cohren turned to Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "But again, their platoon and section leaders know how to get up before their units."
A few seconds later, the rest of the company filed out in mass. Everyone had what they needed, from personal belongings to necessary equipment. Some of the new recruits seemed disoriented, others more annoyed.
"Hello everyone," said Cohren in a cheerful voice.
"Except with all due respect, sir, why do you insist on waking us up this way?" asked one of the shock troop members, a corporal.
"Because standard wake-ups are crap. And because Daybreak doesn't do lazy mornings," replied Cohren.
"Make sure you have all your personal effects," he continued. As the first lieutenant and the commander's assistant, it was his responsibility to supervise and assist the company alongside the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We won't be coming back. Sergeants and second lieutenants, I give you and your units fifty minutes to complete the final checks and retrieve rations for the day."
Members of the Exodus company dispersed. They were part of the second division of the shock troops, second army. Initially, they were separated into two distinct companies, Cohort and Dragger, before being reunited. It was a split company and Cohren didn't know what to think of his promotion to first lieutenant, mainly the reasons that had motivated him.
Cohren and Nemic, the commander of the first platoon, walked together under the light of the numerous floodlights of the forward operational base, powered by generators. Most were tinted red to hide them from enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to both air and ground Wild Weasel attacks to combat them.
"New day, new mission for the pioneers of hell," Nemic began with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"An advanced operational base outside Ianlos. We've been sent to support the land assault," Cohren replied, taking a drag on his cigarette. A part of him blamed Craith for introducing him to tobacco, but a year of combat changes a man, and he remained silent.
"Shit. The situation is deteriorating on the front," muttered Nemic. "All the news coming from there is 'Contribute to the war effort. Send help to the Kurgan front.' Why not send help to the Howland front?"
"Amen, my brother," said Cohren, flicking his cigarette butt into the mud. "In any case, we're leaving with the first armored platoon, so we won't have to walk. Captain Shaw should be here."
"Shaw got us a transport?" asked Nemic, a bit surprised.
"Sure. Honestly, he's not as bad as I thought. I mean, he's not exceptional, but he's not unbearable."
Cohren brought his thumb and index finger to his throat mic while adjusting his backpack. "All Exodus company units, report to the west vehicle park when you're done. We're leaving with the first armored platoon at 5:00."
Every few seconds, he received responses from the squadron leaders. Harris, Craith, and Ravik had all been low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they arrived here. All four had been very close friends since their initial training on Earth. It seemed like such a long time ago, even though it couldn't have been more than two years. They had then been squadron leaders. But Craith had been commanding the second platoon for a week now, after the previous commander was demobilized, wounded by a Daybreak sniper.
As they walked toward the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic saw a group of about eight main battle tanks Kronos and four Strykers. Their crews were busy ensuring their war machines were ready for departure. Cohren quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was talking with the armored platoon commander. As they approached, Shaw turned and walked toward them, his usually cold face showing no emotion.
"Second Lieutenant Nemic... Second Lieutenant Valturi..." He said that Cohren was slower, looking at Cohren's pistol holster before looking at them again. "I suppose the company is ready."
